doc.after: Raccoons are common throughout North America from Canada to Panama, where the subspecies Procyon lotor pumilus coexists with the crab-eating Raccoon (Procyon cancrivorus).[167] The population on Hispaniola was exterminated as early as 1513 by Spanish colonists who hunted them for their meat.[168] Raccoons were also exterminated in Cuba and Jamaica, where the last sightings were reported in 1687.[169] When they were still considered separate species, the Bahamas raccoon, Guadeloupe raccoon and Tres Marias raccoon were classified as endangered by the IUCN in 1996.[170]
